      Rule 2 - No auto-number override:
        The <number/> element is intentionally absent. The auto-number
        engine defined in ../../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case.xml
        generates a CASE0000001-format value on insert per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (the "number" row of the case schema specifies "Auto-
        number" with format CASE0000001 and Read-only constraint).

      Rule 3 - Explicit date overrides (CRITICAL FOR THIS CASE):
        opened_date = "2026-04-10 09:00:00"
            (computed at file generation time as today UTC minus 20
             days at 09:00:00; today=2026-04-30, so today-20=2026-04-10;
             the value is fixed at generation time, NOT evaluated at
             import time, because Update Set XML is a static document)
        closed_date = "2026-04-28 17:00:00"
            (computed at file generation time as today UTC minus 2
             days at 17:00:00; today=2026-04-30, so today-2=2026-04-28)
        Duration = approximately 18 days, 8 hours
            (the small intra-day fraction does not change the AVG
             materially; the widget rounds to days. The 18-day value
             is the LARGER of the two avg-input durations; case 10
             contributes ~14 days, so the two-sample average is ~16
             days.)

        WHY both fields are explicit XML values and not left to the
        business rules (per agent prompt Rule 3):
          * The set_opened_date Before-Insert business rule sets
            opened_date = gs.nowDateTime() at insert time, which would
            yield a value ~20 days AFTER the desired opened_date and
            thereby give a near-zero gap to closed_date.
          * The set_closed_date Before-Update business rule fires only
            on Resolved -> Closed transition, NOT on direct insert with
            status = Closed. So closed_date would remain null on insert
            without an explicit override.
          * Without explicit XML values both date fields would be wrong:
            opened_date would equal "now" (giving zero duration) and
            closed_date would be null (giving NULL duration, which the
            avg_time_to_close report excludes via its
            "closed_date IS NOT NULL" filter).
          * Therefore the agent prompt mandates explicit overrides for
            this canonical Closed-on-insert case.

        WHY the duration differs from case 10 (~14 days):
          The avg_time_to_close widget computes
            AVG(closed_date - opened_date) over Closed cases.
          With only one Closed case the AVG is a constant; with two
          Closed cases having identical durations the AVG is still a
          constant. To make the widget output meaningful and to mimic
          real-world variation, case 06 has a (~20 days, ~2 days)
          opened/closed profile = ~18 days, while case 10 has a
          (~15 days, ~1 day) profile = ~14 days. The two-sample
          average is approximately 16 days, demonstrating that the
          dashboard correctly aggregates across multiple cases with
          differing durations rather than just reporting a constant.

        NOTE on Update Set behavior (per agent prompt Rule 3):
          Update Set imports do NOT trigger Before-Insert/Before-Update
          business rules in the same way as form-based inserts. Some
          PDI configurations DO fire BRs on Update Set commit; others
          do not. To be safe regardless of the importing PDI's setting,
          the explicit opened_date and closed_date values in the XML
          take precedence over any BR-set values: a Before-Insert BR
          that sets opened_date = gs.nowDateTime() will be overridden
          by the XML's explicit value when the XML is imported.

